@Bill - You must be a bit younger than me because I was no longer a wee lad when that book was published. I also used to own a copy. I have no idea what happened to it. 

I don't remember why he felt he needed to explain the Krebs cycle first, other than maybe to introduce the concept of metabolic cycles. The Calvin cycle is much more complex than the Krebs cycle. All the bio textbooks I've seen introduce respiratory metabolism (including the Krebs cycle) first, but Asimov's book was specifically about photosynthesis, so I'm not sure why he chose that tack other than to introduce cycles. 

Anyway, ATP is really just used to provide energy as needed, not to store it. I mean, technically speaking, ALL organic molecules store energy, since all can be oxidized to release energy. I guess any old organic molecule could be used to answer this question.

@Francis - I guess it depends on what the meaning of "storage" is. The ATP pool doesn't "store" much of the total energy in a cell at all. It's really more of a transfer molecule -- it transfers energy. As a rule, once an ATP molecule is made, it lasts for only seconds in an actively metabolizing cell. The resulting ADP (sometimes AMP) is rephosphorylated (recharged with energy) and then used up again. There are no significant cellular energy stores in the form of ATP. Only a small fraction of a cell's energy is in ATP at any given moment. 

And, if simply possessing potential energy is all it takes to qualify as a storage vessel for energy, wouldn't every organic molecule in a cell qualify? 

I just hate propgating misconceptoins.

